      "The dip is not a test of willpower. It is a test of understanding. People quit when they lose the thread between effort and outcome. The solution is not motivation. It is measurement.",
    content: [
      "There is a pattern so consistent it should be a law. A person starts something with energy. The first weeks are electric. Progress is visible. Then the plateau arrives. The gap between effort and visible result widens. And they quit. Not because they are weak. Because the feedback loop broke.",
      "Seth Godin wrote about the dip two decades ago. He framed it as a test of commitment. Push through and you win. We think the framing is incomplete. The dip is not a test of character. It is a failure of information. People quit because they can no longer see whether their effort is producing anything. Remove the blindness, and the quit rate drops.",
      "We see this in every domain we study. Founders quit products that are actually gaining traction because they are looking at the wrong metric. Content creators quit formats that are resonating because they are measuring likes instead of saves. Fitness enthusiasts quit programs that are working because they weigh themselves daily instead of measuring strength monthly.",
      "The pattern is the same. The person is making progress. The measurement system does not reflect it. The person concludes that progress has stopped. They quit. The measurement was the failure, not the effort.",
      "This has enormous implications for product design. Every tool that tracks progress has a responsibility to track the right progress. A fitness app that shows daily weight fluctuations is, in a very real sense, causing people to quit. A social media dashboard that shows follower count instead of engagement depth is causing brands to abandon strategies that were working.",
      "The interesting part of any endeavor is always on the other side of the plateau. In skill development, it is where implicit knowledge begins to form. In business, it is where compounding begins. In creative work, it is where your voice emerges. But the plateau looks like nothing is happening. And without the right measurement, nothing is all you see.",
      "We built Made of Curiosity around this observation. Every product we make is, at its core, a measurement correction. Visualize corrects the measurement of business health. Vines corrects the measurement of content performance. The mission is not productivity. It is visibility. Show people the real signal of their progress and they will do the rest.",
      "The motivation industry is a multi-billion-dollar response to a measurement problem. People do not need more motivation. They need better feedback. They need to see that the thing they are doing is actually working, even when it does not feel like it. The gap between feeling and reality is where quitting lives. Close the gap, and persistence becomes natural.",
      "Next time you want to quit something, before you decide, ask one question: am I measuring the right thing? The answer might change your decision. It might change your year."
    ],
