    readTime: "8 min",
    author: "MOC Research Team",
    summary:
      "Consensus is comfortable. Conviction is useful. The products that change markets are built on theses that most people disagree with. If everyone agrees with your product idea, you are too late.",
    content: [
      "The most dangerous phrase in product development is everyone thinks this is a good idea. If everyone agrees, the market is already crowded. The margin is already compressed. The window is already closing. Consensus is a lagging indicator. By the time the crowd agrees, the opportunity has moved.",
      "Conviction is different. Conviction is a thesis about the world that is supported by evidence but not yet validated by the market. It is the belief that a specific problem exists, that it can be solved in a specific way, and that the market will pay for the solution. Conviction is uncomfortable because it requires you to be right when most people think you are wrong.",
      "Every product at MOC is built on a conviction. Visualize is built on the conviction that founders do not need more data — they need connected data. Most people in the analytics industry disagree. They believe the path forward is more data, more granularity, more features. We believe the path forward is less. That disagreement is our competitive advantage.",
      "Vines is built on the conviction that content strategy should be signal-first, not calendar-first. Most content marketing agencies disagree. They sell consistency and volume. We sell responsiveness and signal. The market will eventually decide who is right. But we are not waiting for the market to decide. We are building as if we already know.",
      "This is the difference between conviction and arrogance. Arrogance ignores evidence. Conviction is built on evidence that others have not yet seen or have chosen to ignore. Our convictions are derived from research. From gap reports. From data. They are not feelings. They are conclusions. And conclusions can be tested.",
      "The cost of consensus-driven product development is mediocrity. If you only build what everyone agrees should be built, you build what already exists. The cost of conviction-driven product development is risk. You might be wrong. But if you are right, you are years ahead of the consensus-driven competitors who will eventually arrive at the same conclusion.",
      "We choose conviction. Not because we enjoy being contrarian. Because we believe that the best products come from theses that are too early for consensus but too supported by evidence to be dismissed. That narrow window between too early and obvious is where category-defining products are born."
    ],
