      "In practical terms, curiosity manifests as research before building, as data before opinion, as observation before thesis. These are not just principles on a website. They are process constraints. You cannot start building a product at MOC without completing the observation phase. You cannot ship a thesis without supporting data. The process enforces the curiosity.",
      "The competitive advantage is real and measurable. Curious teams explore more problem spaces before committing. They validate faster because they ask falsifying questions, not confirming ones. They pivot less because they understood the problem better before they started building. Curiosity is not slow. It is efficient. It front-loads the learning that other teams pay for through failed launches.",
      "We have watched incurious teams build. They start with a solution. They look for a problem that fits. They find one — there is always a problem that sort of fits any solution. They build. They launch. They wonder why adoption is slow. The answer is that they solved a problem nobody prioritized because they never asked who cares about this and how much.",
      "Curiosity is the question that prevents the waste. It is cheap. It is available to everyone. It is the most undervalued competitive advantage in building products. Practice it."
